<subsection xml:id="subsec-construct-angle-of-15-and-75" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Construct Angles Of 15° and 75°</title>

    <p>
        <m>\textbf{(i) Constructing angle 15°}</m>
    </p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>What you need: A ruler, A compass and A pencil.</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a straight line and mark a point <m>A</m> on it as shown below.
                        </p>
                        <image source="/lineA.png" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>
        
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            With <m>A</m> as center draw an arc of any radius to cut the line at <m>B</m>.With the same radius and <m>B</m> as center draw an arc to cut the previous arc at <m>C</m> as shown below.
                        </p>
                        <image source="/angle-60.png" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>
        
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Join <m>AC</m>. Measure angle <m>BAC</m>. Which angle have you constructed?
                        </p>
                        <image source="/angle-60-1.png" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            With <m>B</m> as center, draw an arc of radius more than half of <m>BC</m> in the interior of <m>\angle BAC</m>. With the same radius and with <m>C</m> as center draw an arc to cut the previous one at <m>D</m>.
                        </p>

                        <image source="/angle-30.png" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Join <m>AD</m>. Measure <m>\angle BAD</m>.
                        </p>
                            <image source="/angle-30-1.png" width="60%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (i) Place the compass point on point <m>B</m> and draw an arc within the <m>30°</m> angle.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (ii) Without changing the compass width, place the compass point on point <m></m> and draw another arc that intersects the previous arc; label the intersection point as point <m></m>.
                        </p>

                        <image source="/angle-15.png " width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Join <m>AF</m>. Measure <m>\angle BAF</m>. What do you notice?
                        </p>

                        <image source="/angle-15-1.png" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss your results with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <figure>
        <caption></caption>
        <interactive xml:id="geogebra-angles-15i" platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate xml:id="angles-15i" surface="geogebra" material="wpvpj9tg" aspect="1:1" />
        </interactive>
   </figure>

        <p>
            <m>\textbf{(i)  Constructing angle 75°}</m>
        </p>

        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{what you need:}</m> A Compass, a ruler, a protractor, a pencil and a piece of paper.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a straight line and mark on it point <m>Q</m>. With point <m>Q</m> as the centre, make arcs to cut the line at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as shown below.
                            </p>
                            <image source="/lineABQ.png" width="60%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>
    
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as the centres, make arcs abave and below the line as shown below.
                            </p>
    
                                <image source="/arcs2.png" width="60%">
                                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                </image>
                        </li>
    
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Join points <m>R</m> to <m>S</m> as shown below.measure angle <m>BQR</m> and <m>AQR</m>. Which angles have you constructed?  
                           </p>
    
                           <image source="/angle-90.png" width="60%">
                               <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                           </image>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                               (i) Place the compass point on <m>Q</m> and draw an arc that crosses the line at point <m>B</m>.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                               (ii) Without changing the compass width, place the compass point on <m>B</m> and draw an arc that intersects the first arc; label this intersection as <m>X</m> as shown below. 
                            </p>

                            <image source="/angle-90-60.png" width="60%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a straight line from <m>Q</m> through point <m>X</m> to the other side of the line. Measure angle <m>BQX</m>. What do ypu notice?
                            </p>

                            <image source="/angle60-90-1.png" width="60%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                              (i)  Place the compass point on <m>X</m> and draw an arc between the <m>60°</m> and <m>90°</m> lines.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                (ii) Without changing the compass width, place the compass point on <m>Y</m> and draw another arc that intersects the arc drawn in the previous step; label the intersection point as <m>P</m>.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                (iii) Draw a straight line from <m>Q</m> through <m>P</m>. Measure angle <m>BQP</m>. What do ypu notice?
                            </p>

                            <image source="/angle-75.png" width="60%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Discuss your results with other groups.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
</subsection>